<!-- =========================================================
     MODULE 1: WHAT YOUR SCORE MEANS
     ========================================================= -->
<section id="champ-mod-1" class="champ-module">
  <div class="champ-container">

    <div class="champ-section-label">Your Tier Report</div>
    <div class="champ-divider"></div>

    <h2 class="champ-headline champ-headline--medium">What Scoring 90-100 Actually Means.</h2>

    <p class="champ-body">
      The Champion tier is not an award. It's a behavioral profile. Scoring 90-100 on the Ascend Performance Assessment means that across all eight performance pillars, your behaviors are protocol-driven, not just habitual. There's a meaningful difference between those two things. A habit is what you do because you've done it long enough that it doesn't require thought. A protocol is what you do because you understand the mechanism, you've tested the dose, and you've built the tracking to confirm it's working. Champion athletes operate at the protocol level.
    </p>

    <p class="champ-body">
      What the data shows in the 90-100 range: sleep is not just prioritized, it's tracked. The wake window is within 15 minutes, night to night. Protein isn't just "high" in total grams. It's distributed across four or more meals to repeatedly hit the leucine threshold required to trigger muscle protein synthesis. Training isn't just consistent. It has progressive overload built into the session design. You're not hoping to lift more next week. You've programmed it.
    </p>

    <div class="champ-data-callout">
      <div class="champ-data-callout__stat">Top 5%</div>
      <div class="champ-data-callout__label">Performance Tier Position</div>
      <p class="champ-data-callout__text">
        Champions represent fewer than 1 in 20 athletes assessed. The gap between a 90 and a 70 is not a matter of effort. It's a matter of systematization. You've closed the loop between knowledge and daily execution.
      </p>
    </div>

    <p class="champ-body">
      <strong>The risk profile at this tier is not what most athletes expect.</strong> It's not injury. It's not burnout. It's not information gaps. The primary risk at Champion level is complacency disguised as optimization. Because every pillar is dialed in and you feel elite, the natural human tendency is to loosen precision without noticing it. Creatine timing shifts from exact to approximate. Protein distribution narrows from five meals to three on busy days. Sleep window drifts by 20 minutes, then 30. Progressive overload stalls when you feel strong enough. Each of these individually is minor. Compounded over six months, they represent measurable regression.
    </p>

    <div class="champ-warning">
      <div class="champ-warning__label">Champion Risk Pattern</div>
      <p>
        The most common way Champion athletes decline is not through dramatic failure. It's through incremental drift in behaviors they've stopped actively tracking. When something works, athletes assume it will continue to work without maintenance. That assumption is wrong at the precision level Champion performance requires.
      </p>
    </div>

    <p class="champ-body">
      <strong>Where most Champion athletes get stuck</strong> is at the boundary between maintenance and advancement. They've built an elite performance architecture, and they've internalized the behaviors well enough that they don't feel like effort anymore. That's exactly when drift begins. The discipline that built Champion-level performance is still required to maintain it. The moment you treat your protocols as set and self-sustaining, the compound interest of consistent precision starts eroding.
    </p>

    <p class="champ-body">
      The single most important insight from the Champion tier: performance at this level is not maintained passively. It is defended actively. Every week you do not audit your protocols is a week where drift is possible. The four-week framework in Module 4 addresses this directly.
    </p>

  </div>
</section>


<!-- =========================================================
     MODULE 2: THE CHAMPION PERFORMANCE PROFILE
     ========================================================= -->
<section id="champ-mod-2" class="champ-module champ-module--bg">
  <div class="champ-container">

    <div class="champ-section-label">Your Performance Profile</div>
    <div class="champ-divider"></div>

    <h2 class="champ-headline champ-headline--medium">The Champion Performance Profile.</h2>

    <p class="champ-body">
      There are three behavioral signatures that define Champion athletes. These are not aspirational traits. They are observable patterns that distinguish athletes who consistently score in the 90-100 range from those who score in the 80s. Understanding which of these defines you is how you identify where your next 1% lives.
    </p>

    <div class="champ-behavior-grid">
      <div class="champ-behavior-card">
        <div class="champ-behavior-card__num">01</div>
        <div class="champ-behavior-card__title">Systematized Excellence</div>
        <p class="champ-behavior-card__desc">
          Every pillar is governed by a protocol, not just a preference. Creatine is 5g daily, not "a scoop most days." Sleep target is 10:30 PM, not "when I'm tired." The protocol answers what, how much, and when. The behavior executes it.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="champ-behavior-card">
        <div class="champ-behavior-card__num">02</div>
        <div class="champ-behavior-card__title">Novelty Resistance</div>
        <p class="champ-behavior-card__desc">
          Champion athletes do not chase new systems. When a peer swaps creatine for a "next-gen ATP booster," you don't. When a Reddit thread claims a new supplement stack outperforms everything you're running, you evaluate it against mechanism, not marketing. Refinement beats replacement.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="champ-behavior-card">
        <div class="champ-behavior-card__num">03</div>
        <div class="champ-behavior-card__title">Longevity Awareness</div>
        <p class="champ-behavior-card__desc">
          Champion athletes are thinking beyond the next training block. Joint health, systemic inflammation, cardiovascular infrastructure, hormonal resilience. The question is not "how do I peak for my next competition" but "what does peak performance look like at 40, at 45, at 50?"
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <h3 style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:20px;font-weight:700;color:#0D0D0D;margin:40px 0 16px;letter-spacing:-0.01em;">
      What Separates Champion from Elite: The Behavioral Gap
    </h3>

    <p class="champ-body">
      Athletes in the Elite tier (86-89) have most of the same knowledge as Champions. The gap is execution precision. An Elite athlete takes creatine daily. A Champion athlete takes 5g creatine at a consistent time because they understand that phosphocreatine resynthesis in fast-twitch muscle fibers is concentration-dependent, and variance in dosing creates variance in the buffer that's available during maximal output efforts.
    </p>

    <p class="champ-body">
      Elite athletes distribute protein across meals. Champion athletes know that the leucine content per meal determines whether muscle protein synthesis is actually triggered. 2.5g to 3g of leucine per meal is the threshold. That means each protein meal needs to deliver roughly 30g to 40g of high-quality protein, depending on the source. An Elite athlete might consume 180g of protein in a day and still leave MPS on the table because three of their four meals delivered 20g instead of 35g.
    </p>

    <div class="champ-comparison-grid">
      <div class="champ-comparison-col">
        <div class="champ-comparison-col__header">Champion (90-100)</div>
        <div class="champ-comparison-cell champ-comparison-cell--champion">5g creatine daily, consistent timing, confirmed intake log</div>
        <div class="champ-comparison-cell champ-comparison-cell--champion">4-5 protein meals, 30g+ per meal, leucine-threshold aware</div>
        <div class="champ-comparison-cell champ-comparison-cell--champion">Sleep window within 15 minutes, tracked, consistent across work days and weekends</div>
        <div class="champ-comparison-cell champ-comparison-cell--champion">Progressive overload programmed. Deload scheduled at 4-6 week intervals.</div>
        <div class="champ-comparison-cell champ-comparison-cell--champion">Supplement timing is protocol-level. AM, pre-training, post-training, PM all defined.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="champ-comparison-col">
        <div class="champ-comparison-col__header">Elite (86-89)</div>
        <div class="champ-comparison-cell">Takes creatine most days. Dose varies between 3g and 6g.</div>
        <div class="champ-comparison-cell">High daily protein total. Distribution is inconsistent across meals.</div>
        <div class="champ-comparison-cell">Prioritizes sleep and usually hits target. Weekend variance up to 45-60 minutes.</div>
        <div class="champ-comparison-cell">Trains hard and progressively. Deloads when fatigued, not on a schedule.</div>
        <div class="champ-comparison-cell">Supplements consistently. Timing is habitual rather than protocol-defined.</div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <h3 style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:20px;font-weight:700;color:#0D0D0D;margin:40px 0 16px;letter-spacing:-0.01em;">
      The Common Champion Mistake
    </h3>

    <p class="champ-body">
      Champion athletes stop progressive overload when they feel strong. They feel strong because they are strong. But the mechanism of progressive overload is not dependent on whether you feel like you need it. Hypertrophic adaptation requires a stimulus that exceeds what the tissue has already adapted to. Once you feel "good" at a given load, you've adapted to it. Continuing that load without change maintains current muscle mass at best. It does not build more. It does not improve performance. It merely sustains the adaptation you've already accumulated.
    </p>

    <p class="champ-body">
      The same principle applies to deloads. Most Champion athletes in the 90-100 range skip deloads during phases where they feel good and performance is high. This is the wrong trigger. Deloads are not a response to feeling bad. They're a mechanism for allowing neuromuscular fatigue to dissipate so the next training block starts from a fully recovered baseline. Research from Zatsiorsky and Kraemer on the fitness-fatigue model is clear: accumulated training stress masks fitness. A properly timed deload reveals what your body is actually capable of after fatigue is removed. That's when new PRs happen.
    </p>

    <div class="champ-warning">
      <div class="champ-warning__label">The Complacency Pattern</div>
      <p>
        Six months of "feels good enough" without active protocol audit produces a 5-10% measurable regression in performance metrics for most Champion-tier athletes. The regression is invisible month to month. Quarterly tracking reveals it. This is why the Week 4 baseline update in the Champion framework is non-negotiable.
      </p>
    </div>

    <h3 style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:20px;font-weight:700;color:#0D0D0D;margin:40px 0 16px;letter-spacing:-0.01em;">
      The Longevity Question
    </h3>

    <p class="champ-body">
      Sustaining Champion-level performance over a 5 to 10-year horizon requires a different lens than sustaining it month to month. The variables that govern long-term sustained output are not the same as the ones governing peak performance for a single competition. Systemic inflammation accumulation, hormonal axis resilience, cardiovascular infrastructure, bone density maintenance, and connective tissue health become progressively more determinative of your ceiling as you age.
    </p>

    <p class="champ-body">
      Athletes who perform at elite levels in their 20s and maintain it through their 30s and 40s consistently share one characteristic: they added longevity infrastructure to their performance stack before they needed it. Omega-3 EPA/DHA at therapeutic doses (2g to 3g daily) reduces inflammatory cytokine load. Vitamin D at 3,000 to 5,000IU supports testosterone synthesis and bone mineral density. Curcumin with piperine reduces NF-kB pathway activation, the central mechanism of systemic inflammation. These are not recovery tools. They are compound interest for your body's structural integrity.
    </p>

    <div class="champ-pull-quote">
      <p>"You're in the top 5%. That is not luck. That is the result of decisions made over hundreds of days when no one was watching. The question now is what you're going to do with it. Protecting this is not passive. It requires the same intention that built it."</p>
    </div>

  </div>
</section>


