<!-- =========================================================
     MODULE 4: THE CHAMPION PRIORITY FRAMEWORK
     ========================================================= -->
<section id="champ-mod-4" class="champ-module champ-module--bg">
  <div class="champ-container">

    <div class="champ-section-label">The Framework</div>
    <div class="champ-divider"></div>

    <h2 class="champ-headline champ-headline--medium">The Champion Priority Framework.</h2>

    <p class="champ-body">
      The Champion mental model has three components. Together, they define the operating system for anyone trying to sustain elite-level performance across years, not just training blocks.
    </p>

    <div style="display:grid;grid-template-columns:1fr 1fr 1fr;gap:1px;background:#E5E7EB;margin:32px 0;overflow:hidden;">
      <div style="background:white;padding:24px 20px;text-align:center;">
        <div style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:3px;color:#06A5C5;margin-bottom:10px;">Pillar One</div>
        <div style="font-family:Georgia,serif;font-size:20px;font-weight:700;color:#0D0D0D;margin-bottom:8px;">Protect the Build</div>
        <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:13px;color:#333333;line-height:1.6;">Audit every protocol. Identify drift before it compounds. The architecture you've built took years. Guard it with weekly intention.</p>
      </div>
      <div style="background:white;padding:24px 20px;text-align:center;">
        <div style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:3px;color:#06A5C5;margin-bottom:10px;">Pillar Two</div>
        <div style="font-family:Georgia,serif;font-size:20px;font-weight:700;color:#0D0D0D;margin-bottom:8px;">Compound What Works</div>
        <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:13px;color:#333333;line-height:1.6;">Identify the specific behaviors producing the highest returns. Increase their precision and consistency. Don't dilute them by layering in novelty.</p>
      </div>
      <div style="background:white;padding:24px 20px;text-align:center;">
        <div style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:3px;color:#06A5C5;margin-bottom:10px;">Pillar Three</div>
        <div style="font-family:Georgia,serif;font-size:20px;font-weight:700;color:#0D0D0D;margin-bottom:8px;">Resist Novelty</div>
        <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:13px;color:#333333;line-height:1.6;">Every new protocol is a withdrawal from your current compound interest account. Unless mechanism and evidence are solid, the default answer is no. What you have is working.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <p class="champ-body">
      The question at Champion level is not "what should I change?" The right question is: "What earned behaviors am I at risk of drifting from?" That reframe is the entire framework. Maintenance is not passive. It is an active discipline that requires the same intention and tracking that built your current level.
    </p>

    <div class="champ-sep"></div>

    <h3 style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:22px;font-weight:700;color:#0D0D0D;margin:0 0 24px;letter-spacing:-0.01em;">
      Your 4-Week Champion Protocol
    </h3>

    <!-- WEEK 1 -->
    <div class="champ-week-block">
      <div class="champ-week-block__header">
        <div class="champ-week-block__num">01</div>
        <div>
          <div class="champ-week-block__title">Protocol Audit</div>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="champ-week-block__body">
        <div class="champ-week-block__focus">Focus: Confirm, Not Change</div>
        <div class="champ-week-block__content">
          <p>Week 1 is not about fixing anything. It's about confirming everything. Champion athletes who skip the audit phase assume that because performance feels good, precision is intact. That assumption creates the opening for drift. The audit reveals the gap between what you believe you're doing and what you're actually doing.</p>
          <ul>
            <li>Verify creatine is still at exactly 5g daily. Not "a scoop." Measure it. If your scoop has varied between 4g and 7g, the protocol has drifted.</li>
            <li>Confirm protein distribution: are you genuinely hitting 30g or more across four separate meals, or have two of those meals dropped to 20g? Log one full day this week.</li>
            <li>Check your sleep wake window. Pull the last 14 nights from your tracker. Is the wake time within 15 minutes night to night? If the weekends are showing a 45-minute drift, your circadian rhythm is not as dialed as your weekday behavior suggests.</li>
            <li>Confirm supplement timing is protocol-level, not approximate. When exactly are you taking what? Write it down.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="champ-assignment">
      <div class="champ-assignment__label">Your Assignment</div>
      <p>Complete a written protocol audit for all eight pillars. Not a mental review. Write it down. For each pillar, document: what your current protocol says, what you're actually doing, and whether there's a gap. This document becomes your Champion baseline. You'll return to it in Week 4.</p>
    </div>

    <!-- WEEK 2 -->
    <div class="champ-week-block">
      <div class="champ-week-block__header">
        <div class="champ-week-block__num">02</div>
        <div>
          <div class="champ-week-block__title">Longevity Infrastructure</div>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="champ-week-block__body">
        <div class="champ-week-block__focus">Focus: The Stack You Build Before You Need It</div>
        <div class="champ-week-block__content">
          <p>Longevity infrastructure is not recovery support. It's systemic protection for an athlete who intends to perform at this level for the next decade. Week 2 is about confirming or building the supplement architecture that protects long-term output capacity.</p>
          <ul>
            <li>Omega-3: confirm your daily EPA/DHA dose is between 2g and 3g of actual combined EPA and DHA (not total fish oil milligrams). This dose range is associated with significant reductions in inflammatory markers including CRP and IL-6. Most fish oil products require 3 to 4 softgels to reach this dose. Verify your label.</li>
            <li>Vitamin D: confirm 3,000 to 5,000IU daily. Vitamin D3 is the form with the most robust evidence for testosterone synthesis support and bone mineral density maintenance. Best taken with a fat-containing meal for absorption.</li>
            <li>Magnesium glycinate at 400mg PM: glycinate form crosses the blood-brain barrier more effectively than magnesium oxide and has been shown to support GABA receptor activity, reducing sleep-onset latency and improving slow-wave sleep duration.</li>
            <li>Assess joint inflammation signals: morning stiffness in wrists, knees, or shoulders lasting more than 10 minutes. Chronic aching in high-volume joints. If either is present, add curcumin with piperine (Balance) for NF-kB pathway management.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="champ-assignment">
      <div class="champ-assignment__label">Your Assignment</div>
      <p>Review your current supplement stack against the longevity infrastructure checklist: Omega-3 dose confirmed at 2-3g EPA/DHA. Vitamin D at 3,000-5,000IU. Magnesium glycinate at 400mg PM. Add what is missing. Confirm doses of what is present. If you are supplementing fish oil but have never verified the actual EPA/DHA content on the label, do that today.</p>
    </div>

    <!-- WEEK 3 -->
    <div class="champ-week-block">
      <div class="champ-week-block__header">
        <div class="champ-week-block__num">03</div>
        <div>
          <div class="champ-week-block__title">Training Review</div>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="champ-week-block__body">
        <div class="champ-week-block__focus">Focus: Progressive Overload Audit and Deload Assessment</div>
        <div class="champ-week-block__content">
          <p>Week 3 addresses the training variables most commonly drifting at Champion level. Progressive overload is not a feeling. It's a measurable variable: volume (sets times reps), load (weight on bar), intensity (percentage of 1RM), or training density (work per unit of time). One of these must be increasing over time, or you are maintaining, not building.</p>
          <ul>
            <li>Pull your training log from the last 8 weeks. Identify the primary compound movements (squat, deadlift, press, row, or sport-specific equivalents). Have the numbers gone up? If they've been flat for 4 weeks or more, you've stopped progressive overload, even if you're training hard.</li>
            <li>Identify which variable to address. If load has plateaued, consider volume increase (add a set). If volume is high, consider intensity (drop reps, add weight). If both are constrained, consider frequency (add a session) or exercise selection (rotate a movement to re-introduce novelty stimulus).</li>
            <li>Deload timing: when was your last deload week? A deload is 40-60% of normal volume at 50-60% of normal intensity, lasting 5 to 7 days. If it's been more than 6 weeks since your last deload, schedule one this week. Neuromuscular fatigue accumulates invisibly. The performance you think you're expressing is masked by the fatigue layered on top of it.</li>
            <li>Post-deload testing: after a properly executed deload, test a primary lift. Performance should be up, not down. If you've been skipping deloads and you test post-deload, the number tells you exactly what fatigue has been costing you.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="champ-assignment">
      <div class="champ-assignment__label">Your Assignment</div>
      <p>Review 8 weeks of training data for one primary compound movement per major pattern (push, pull, hinge, squat). Confirm progressive overload is present. Confirm last deload date. If overdue, execute a deload this week. Log the outcome and note how your performance changes in the first training session of the subsequent week.</p>
    </div>

    <!-- SCRIPTURE (mid-protocol, natural placement) -->
    <div class="champ-scripture">
      <p class="champ-scripture__text">
        "Have I not commanded you? Be strong and courageous. Do not be frightened, and do not be dismayed, for the Lord your God is with you wherever you go."
      </p>
      <div class="champ-scripture__citation">Joshua 1:9</div>
    </div>

    <p class="champ-body">
      That verse is not about a training block. It's about the kind of sustained courage required to stay disciplined when the urgency is gone and the results feel automatic. Champion athletes face a version of this. You've done the work. It's paying off. The temptation is to ease up. Strength at this stage is not grinding harder. It's staying exact when approximation would feel fine.
    </p>

    <!-- WEEK 4 -->
    <div class="champ-week-block">
      <div class="champ-week-block__header">
        <div class="champ-week-block__num">04</div>
        <div>
          <div class="champ-week-block__title">Full Baseline Update</div>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="champ-week-block__body">
        <div class="champ-week-block__focus">Focus: Score All 8 Pillars. Set the Next 30-Day Priority.</div>
        <div class="champ-week-block__content">
          <p>Week 4 closes the loop. You audited in Week 1. You confirmed longevity infrastructure in Week 2. You addressed training variables in Week 3. Week 4 is the baseline update that makes this a cycle rather than a one-time event.</p>
          <ul>
            <li>Subjectively score each of the 8 performance pillars on a 1-10 scale: sleep, nutrition, training, recovery, supplementation, stress management, hydration, mental performance. Note which have moved since Week 1 and which are still below where you want them.</li>
            <li>Compare against your Week 1 audit document. Has the drift you identified been corrected? Are any new drifts visible that weren't apparent in Week 1?</li>
            <li>The pillar with the lowest subjective score becomes the priority for the next 30 days. Not the one that feels the most broken. The lowest one. Even if it's a 7 out of 10. At Champion level, a 7 out of 10 in any pillar represents significant available performance.</li>
            <li>Retake the Ascend Performance Quiz. Your score at Week 4 reflects where you're actually operating, post-audit. Use it as your updated baseline for the next cycle.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="champ-assignment">
      <div class="champ-assignment__label">Your Assignment</div>
